⏺ Two good adds. Let me take the SVG one head-on since it's a real architectural fork, then the autopsy pick.

  SVG — the "slow" rumor is real but narrow and dated, and it doesn't bite us where we'd use it. The thing to separate is
  generating SVG vs rendering it:

  - Generating SVG text — trivially cheap, and it's exactly incant's wheelhouse (spit text). Zero concern.
  - Rendering SVG — this is where "slow" comes from, and it's specifically DOM-SVG: inline <svg> in a browser where every
  element is a live DOM node carrying CSS cascade, hit-testing, and relayout. At tens of thousands of nodes, or re-rendered
  every frame for animation, that bogs. The rumors trace to ~2008–2012 browser engines; modern ones are far better, but
  DOM-SVG still degrades at high node counts. Native rasterizers (resvg, librsvg, Skia, CoreGraphics) render SVG as a fast
  one-shot — the rumor never applied to those.

  So the honest split: SVG is the perfect emission / debug / portability / static-UI layer; it's the wrong thing to
  round-trip per frame for interactive/animated drawing. And here's the elegant part — that maps exactly onto the "one
  instruction list, multiple renderers" pattern we just salvaged from the old GUI (drawDetail Cocoa + drawPDFdetail libHaru
  over the same tree). SVG just becomes a third renderer sibling — and it's the cheapest one to build first (pure text),
  which makes it the ideal POP sink. Then:
  - SVG renderer → debug dumps + non-Apple/browser rendering (dovetails with the incant→HTML portability bridge already on
  the books).
  - Native renderer (CGPath/NSBezierPath at the leaf externs) → the interactive hot path, where you lower the instruction
  list straight to native primitives instead of round-tripping through SVG-DOM.

  Net: SVG is not either/or. Build it first as the text-dump POP sink (instant visual verify in any browser), keep native as
  the performance path later. You were right to reach for it.

